x;">Meanwhile, Kirk is not the doofus that many liberals conjure: He came t=
o play. A podcast
host himself, he trucked Newsom in the episode=E2=80=99s first 30 minutes w=
ith a burst of facts and arguments about Gen Z and the failures of elite ed=
ucation. If Newsom was cosplaying as a journalist, he forgot to study his n=
ote cards. When Kirk jabbed his finger at Newsom and said he =E2=80=9Csuppo=
rted Prop 16 that institutionalized racism in California,=E2=80=9D Newsom s=
tammered and didn=E2=80=99t bother to push back or explain his thinking on =
the 2020 ballot measure that brought Affirmative Action back to the state. =
Also
not working in Newsom=E2=80=99s favor: He has a few characteristic verbal t=
ics=E2=80=94=E2=80=9CI love that=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9CI totally appreciate =
that=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94that probably make him sound agreeable in a room full=
 of lawmakers or voters, but that don=E2=80=99t work when you=E2=80=99re po=
dcasting with a guy accusing you of reverse racism and managing a socialist=
 dystopia.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">But there are signs of improvement. Ne=
wsom dropped Episode 2 on Monday night=E2=80=94an extended
conversation with conservative radio host <strong>Michael Savage</strong>, =
himself a longtime California resident.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margi=
n-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">You can t=
ell Newsom had received some feedback since his audio debut: He=E2=80=99s m=
ore jolly and agreeable with Savage, while also pushing back with more freq=
uency and detail on issues like climate and homelessness than he did with K=
irk. Still, given Newsom=E2=80=99s willingness to engage with figures
that progressives have vilified for years, Democrats might not like this ep=
isode either=E2=80=94or any of them, ever, for that matter. =E2=80=9CDonald=
 Trump and I are getting along right now!=E2=80=9D Newsom tells Savage at o=
ne point with a laugh. A few minutes later, Newsom asks his guest =E2=80=9C=
what the hell=E2=80=9D the Democratic Party needs to do. =E2=80=9CWas it be=
cause we were too woke? We didn=E2=80=99t focus enough on borders? What was=
 it?=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin:0;"><br/>Controversy or not, it=E2=80=
=99s clear after Episode 2 that Newsom is going to
keep podcasting through it. He might actually might have a hit on his hands=
=2E The debut episode of <em>This Is Ga=
vin Newsom</em> reached as high as No.=
 4 overall on Apple Podcasts last week, and No. 1 in news over the weekend.=
 Newsom also seems to understand a key MAGA insight about =E2=80=9Cwinning=
=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94attention is everything in the war of ideas, eyeballs, an=
d potential new voters. Both Newsom and Kirk posted the full episode of the=
 podcast on their respective YouTube accounts, and between both channels,
the debut has over 1.3 million views and counting. Adding in view counts fr=
om TikTok and YouTube, clips from the first episode of <em>This Is Gavin Ne=
wsom</em> now have over 7.2 million combined views. As for what=E2=80=99s n=
ext? More MAGA listening sessions. I=E2=80=99ve learned that Newsom recorde=
d a conversation with none other than <strong>Steve Bannon</strong> on Tues=
day, an episode set to go live overnight.=C2=A0</p></div>
